rticularly in the elderly and those with underlying organic brain disease, who tend to be more sensitive to the central anticholinergic effects of these drugs and in whom toxicity symptoms may be easily overlooked.', 'Moderate', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/20016/', '[1] "Product Information. Symmetrel (amantadine)." DuPont Pharmaceuticals, Wilmington, DE.[2] Postma JU, van Tilburg W "Visual hallucinations and delirium during treatment with amantadine (Symmetrel)." J Am Geriatr Soc 23 (1975): 212-5[3] Warrington SJ, Ankier SI, Turner P "Evaluation of possible interactions between ethanol and trazodone or amitriptyline." Neuropsychobiology 15 (1986): 31-7[4] "Product Information. Fycompa (perampanel)." Eisai Inc, Teaneck, NJ.[5] "Product Information. Rexulti (brexpiprazole)." Otsuka American Pharmaceuticals Inc, Rockville, MD.[6] Gilman AG, Rall TW, Nies AS, Taylor P, eds. "Goodman and Gilman''s the Pharmacological Basis of Therapeutics. 8th ed." New York, NY: Pergamon Press Inc. (1990):', 'Cabergoline', 'Ketotifen, Levocetirizine, Trimethobenzamide, Loratadine, Desloratadine, Azelastine, Terfenadine, Astemizole', 1767369485);
